00:00:02.360 --> 00:00:03.770
Welcome, everyone.

00:00:03.770 --> 00:00:06.970
A "Forbes" article
about Meb Faber's book

00:00:06.970 --> 00:00:10.400
begins with the question, how
does an investment manager

00:00:10.400 --> 00:00:14.190
reconcile all of the
various prognostications

00:00:14.190 --> 00:00:16.650
he hears on a daily basis?

00:00:16.650 --> 00:00:20.700
His curt and brief
response was, ignore them.

00:00:20.700 --> 00:00:23.590
Over 70 years ago, Ben
Graham and David Dodd

00:00:23.590 --> 00:00:26.050
proposed valuing
stocks with earnings

00:00:26.050 --> 00:00:28.610
smoothed across multiple years.

00:00:28.610 --> 00:00:30.680
Robert Shiller later
popularized this method

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:34.430
with his version of the
cyclically adjusted price

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:39.200
to earnings, or the cape
ratio, in the late 1990s

00:00:39.200 --> 00:00:42.710
and correctly issued a timely
warning of poor stock returns

00:00:42.710 --> 00:00:45.620
to follow in the coming years.

00:00:45.620 --> 00:00:50.120
Our speaker today Mr. Faber
applies this valuation metric

00:00:50.120 --> 00:00:52.440
across his global investments.

00:00:52.440 --> 00:00:57.130
He's a co-founder and CIO of
Cambria Investment Management

00:00:57.130 --> 00:01:00.420
and has authored numerous
white papers and three books--

00:01:00.420 --> 00:01:05.129
"Shareholder Yield," "The Ivy
Portfolio," and "Global Value."

00:01:05.129 --> 00:01:07.810
A frequent speaker and writer
on investment strategies

00:01:07.810 --> 00:01:10.000
who has been featured
in the "Barons,"

00:01:10.000 --> 00:01:12.030
"The New York Times,"
and "The New Yorker,"

00:01:12.030 --> 00:01:17.010
he is here today to speak
about his investing philosophy.

00:01:17.010 --> 00:01:20.730
So without further ado, friends,
let's welcome Mebane Faber.

