But this isn't anything.

00:11:13.669 --> 00:11:16.210
This is something that's been
going on for hundreds of years.

00:11:16.210 --> 00:11:19.260
This is an example that goes
back to the early 18th century.

00:11:19.260 --> 00:11:21.200
This is in a paper we
wrote called Learning

00:11:21.200 --> 00:11:22.720
to Love Investment Bubbles.

00:11:22.720 --> 00:11:25.460
But this is an example of one
of the most famous bubbles.

00:11:25.460 --> 00:11:27.320
And there's some great
books on this topic.

00:11:27.320 --> 00:11:30.230
"Extraordinary Popular Delusions
and the Madness of Crowds"

00:11:30.230 --> 00:11:31.850
is a really
wonderful one-- talks

00:11:31.850 --> 00:11:34.410
about many historical bubbles.

00:11:34.410 --> 00:11:37.870
What this shows is an example
of a stock that went parabolic

00:11:37.870 --> 00:11:39.270
in the early 18th century.

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:41.210
It was a [INAUDIBLE] stock.

00:11:41.210 --> 00:11:42.510
We talk about it in this paper.

00:11:42.510 --> 00:11:44.290
It's a really interesting story.

00:11:44.290 --> 00:11:46.770
It involves a lot of the
things that typically happen

00:11:46.770 --> 00:11:49.290
in bubbles-- easy access
to money, credit, people

00:11:49.290 --> 00:11:49.950
borrowing.

00:11:49.950 --> 00:11:52.550
But the most important one is
people making a lot of money.

00:11:52.550 --> 00:11:57.300
And a very great example is one
of the most rational, brilliant

00:11:57.300 --> 00:11:59.730
scientists of all
times, Sir Isaac Newton,

00:11:59.730 --> 00:12:01.190
was an investor in this company.

00:12:01.190 --> 00:12:03.700
It goes to show his
experience that will probably

00:12:03.700 --> 00:12:06.009
mimic a lot of
investors experiences

00:12:06.009 --> 00:12:08.050
in stock that went parabolic
and went in bubbles.

00:12:08.050 --> 00:12:11.995
So an example-- I joke a
lot on my blog and Twitter

00:12:11.995 --> 00:12:15.280
that this probably looks like
a chart of Bitcoin, to which I

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:18.044
get a lot of hate
mail about, strangely.

00:12:18.044 --> 00:12:19.460
I've been writing
for seven years.

00:12:19.460 --> 00:12:22.530
And all of a sudden, I
start getting hate mail.

00:12:22.530 --> 00:12:23.620
Anyway, so this example.

00:12:23.620 --> 00:12:27.170
So Neuton buys in,
doubles his money.

00:12:27.170 --> 00:12:27.801
What is that?

00:12:27.801 --> 00:12:28.800
Yeah, doubles his money.

00:12:28.800 --> 00:12:30.230
Could not be happier.

00:12:30.230 --> 00:12:33.130
What's the worst
possible thing when

00:12:33.130 --> 00:12:34.760
you've made money
and gotten out?

00:12:34.760 --> 00:12:38.436
Well, it's that your friends
are making more money, right?

00:12:38.436 --> 00:12:39.810
Someone just sold
an app company.

00:12:39.810 --> 00:12:41.340
Uber's valued at $18 billion.

00:12:41.340 --> 00:12:43.770
Someone else did this
Yo app that's getting

00:12:43.770 --> 00:12:45.080
millions of downloads, right?

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:46.920
What's the worst possible
thing that could happen?

00:12:46.920 --> 00:12:48.270
It's your friend
in the next cubicle

00:12:48.270 --> 00:12:49.270
is making more money than you.

00:12:49.270 --> 00:12:51.546
Or your friends are all
getting rich but you're not.

00:12:51.546 --> 00:12:52.670
So what happens, of course?

00:12:52.670 --> 00:12:56.399
Well, then he decides
to buy back in, OK?

00:12:56.399 --> 00:12:58.690
Well, of course, he's buying
near the top, at the peak.

00:12:58.690 --> 00:12:59.231
What happens?

00:12:59.231 --> 00:13:00.220
It crashes 90%.

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:02.670
Well, then he sells
at the bottom, OK?

00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:06.020
Well, this is something that
happens over and over again

00:13:06.020 --> 00:13:07.470
in investing.

00:13:07.470 --> 00:13:10.280
And so I just want to
show it's nothing new.

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:12.850
And think about this
as we go forward.

00:13:12.850 --> 00:13:14.670
So what can you do?

00:13:14.670 --> 00:13:17.990
Is there anything you can do to
remove this emotional decision

00:13:17.990 --> 00:13:22.770
making to combat our
behavioral biases?

00:13:22.770 --> 00:13:24.980
Well, so there are these
two good looking guys

00:13:24.980 --> 00:13:27.010
you may recognize, may not.

00:13:27.010 --> 00:13:28.910
On the left is Ben
Graham, often known

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:30.600
as the father of
security analysis.

00:13:30.600 --> 00:13:32.490
He wrote a couple great books.

00:13:32.490 --> 00:13:34.590
He's a professor
early 20th century

00:13:34.590 --> 00:13:37.250
called "Security Analysis--
An Intelligent Investor."

00:13:37.250 --> 00:13:40.420
And what he proposed is,
when looking at an investment

00:13:40.420 --> 00:13:46.390
to value the company and often
to smooth out the valuation

00:13:46.390 --> 00:13:48.290
by using earnings over
a number of years.

00:13:48.290 --> 00:13:49.570
Not just looking at
one year of earnings,

00:13:49.570 --> 00:13:51.990
but his preferred metric was
smoothing it out over five

00:13:51.990 --> 00:13:52.760
to seven years.

00:13:52.760 --> 00:13:55.010
There's a way to smooth out
the business cycle, right?

00:13:55.010 --> 00:13:57.410
As a way to have a
fundamental anchor

00:13:57.410 --> 00:14:00.400
to be able to compare companies
to each other on a long term

00:14:00.400 --> 00:14:02.200
basis.

00:14:02.200 --> 00:14:04.620
Fast forward 80 years later--
so this is nothing new.

00:14:04.620 --> 00:14:06.460
This has been around
almost a century.

00:14:06.460 --> 00:14:08.800
Robert Shiller,
recent Nobel laureate,

00:14:08.800 --> 00:14:11.900
just won with Eugene
Fama, professor at Yale.

00:14:11.900 --> 00:14:13.840
He put out a white
paper in the late '90s

00:14:13.840 --> 00:14:15.230
called "Irrational Exuberance."

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:17.190
Sorry, excuse me, a
white paper, then a book

00:14:17.190 --> 00:14:18.481
called "Irrational Exuberance."

00:14:18.481 --> 00:14:20.930
Alan Greenspan later used
the term in Congress,

00:14:20.930 --> 00:14:23.836
promptly sent the stock
market down quite a bit.

00:14:23.836 --> 00:14:25.460
But he says, let's
take a look at this.

00:14:25.460 --> 00:14:28.550
But let's use it on the
market-wide basis as a whole.

00:14:28.550 --> 00:14:31.310
Let's look at 10 year average
earnings across the entire US

00:14:31.310 --> 00:14:34.570
stock market called the 10
year Cyclically Adjusted Price

00:14:34.570 --> 00:14:36.620
Earnings ratio-- CAPE, right?

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:39.720
So this is an example of what
that looks like back to 1881.

00:14:39.720 --> 00:14:41.185
So that's a long time.

00:14:41.185 --> 00:14:44.170
And the problem you have with
efficient market people--

00:14:44.170 --> 00:14:46.080
people that say, the
market's efficient.

00:14:46.080 --> 00:14:48.770
You can't predict bubbles--
or sorry, bubble don't exist.

00:14:48.770 --> 00:14:49.820
First of all, they say,
bubbles don't exist.

00:14:49.820 --> 00:14:50.500
They do exist.

00:14:50.500 --> 00:14:51.920
You can't predict them.

00:14:51.920 --> 00:14:53.734
And that doesn't make
much sense to me.

00:14:53.734 --> 00:14:55.150
If you look at
this chart, there's

00:14:55.150 --> 00:14:58.090
an average value of around
16, 17 times earnings,

00:14:58.090 --> 00:15:00.640
right, that the US stock
market has been in.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:03.020
There's times when it's
been incredibly low,

00:15:03.020 --> 00:15:06.510
in the low single digits--
think 1910s as well

00:15:06.510 --> 00:15:07.590
as post depression.

00:15:07.590 --> 00:15:10.150
But there's also times when
things get incredibly bubbly.

00:15:10.150 --> 00:15:12.889
If you look at the late '20s,
you get to a value of over 30.

00:15:12.889 --> 00:15:14.930
If you look at the biggest
bubble in the US stock

00:15:14.930 --> 00:15:18.020
market's ever seen in the late
'90s, you have a value of 45.

00:15:18.020 --> 00:15:20.100
Does it seem even
remotely reasonable

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:22.680
that it is a good a time to
buy stocks when they're trading

00:15:22.680 --> 00:15:25.480
at 45 times earnings
in 1999 as it

00:15:25.480 --> 00:15:29.790
was in the early 1980s
at a value of five?

00:15:29.790 --> 00:15:33.210
That does not pass a common
sense sniff test for me.

00:15:33.210 --> 00:15:36.170
So if you look at this, you
say that OK, does it work?

00:15:36.170 --> 00:15:39.350
Historically, being a scientist,
an engineer, does this work?

00:15:39.350 --> 00:15:41.100
Historically, it's worked great.

00:15:41.100 --> 00:15:43.340
If you buy stock market
when it's cheap at, say,

00:15:43.340 --> 00:15:46.800
less than a CAPE ratio of 10,
you get great future returns.

00:15:46.800 --> 00:15:49.230
These are 10 returns going
forward-- real returns.

00:15:49.230 --> 00:15:53.030
So we're netting out inflation.

00:15:53.030 --> 00:15:55.800
And it's a nice stair step down.

00:15:55.800 --> 00:15:59.076
The more you pay for stocks, the
lower your future returns are.

00:15:59.076 --> 00:16:00.700
It is-- again, it's
not rocket science.

00:16:00.700 --> 00:16:02.860
It's simple.

00:16:02.860 --> 00:16:05.830
But this works out over
a long term time horizon.

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:09.530
If you look at where we are now,
we're at a value of around 26.

00:16:09.530 --> 00:16:12.490
So unfortunately,
in the worst bucket

00:16:12.490 --> 00:16:15.240
where the red line is right
now where future returns should

00:16:15.240 --> 00:16:17.660
be pretty muted, pretty low.

00:16:17.660 --> 00:16:19.370
We don't think it's a bubble.

00:16:19.370 --> 00:16:20.450
It's not crazy.

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:22.850
But I was talking about
this at lunch today.

00:16:22.850 --> 00:16:25.470
There's a spectrum of
future returns, right?

00:16:25.470 --> 00:16:27.729
And simply, the more
the market goes up

00:16:27.729 --> 00:16:30.020
in the meantime means the
lower your future returns are

00:16:30.020 --> 00:16:31.110
going to be.

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:33.350
The more the market goes
down in the meantime,

00:16:33.350 --> 00:16:35.884
the higher your future returns
are going to be in general.

00:16:35.884 --> 00:16:37.300
The best possible
thing that could

00:16:37.300 --> 00:16:39.799
happen, if you're a young person
in this room, is the market

00:16:39.799 --> 00:16:42.730
could crash by 50%.

00:16:42.730 --> 00:16:45.370
Maybe the best possible thing,
but the best possible thing

00:16:45.370 --> 00:16:46.880
for your investing career.

00:16:46.880 --> 00:16:49.796
Because you can then invest
in the US for the next 10, 20,

00:16:49.796 --> 00:16:52.250
30, 40 years at a much
cheaper valuation.

00:16:52.250 --> 00:16:54.879
That is not the opportunity
set right now, unfortunately.

00:16:54.879 --> 00:16:56.670
We're going to stop on
this one real quick.

00:16:56.670 --> 00:16:59.740
It's just a scatter plot for
the nerds out there like me

00:16:59.740 --> 00:17:02.810
that goes to show that
valuation-- it looks almost

00:17:02.810 --> 00:17:04.079
like a shotgun blast, right?

00:17:04.079 --> 00:17:05.800
Doesn't explain everything.

00:17:05.800 --> 00:17:07.490
We're in kind of
the yellow area.

00:17:07.490 --> 00:17:10.520
But in general, the more
expensive you pay for stocks,

00:17:10.520 --> 00:17:12.099
the worse the
future returns are.

00:17:12.099 --> 00:17:14.980
The less you pay for them, the
better the future returns are.

00:17:14.980 --> 00:17:16.619
I don't expect you
to see this chart.

00:17:16.619 --> 00:17:19.658
I don't expect you to really
even appreciate what it is.

00:17:19.658 --> 00:17:21.407
From just the colors,
it looks like a bowl

00:17:21.407 --> 00:17:22.740
of, like, Fruity Pebbles, right?

00:17:22.740 --> 00:17:25.410
But what this is-- this
is CAPE ratio buckets.

00:17:25.410 --> 00:17:28.860
So the dark green, or the
cheapest buckets, all the way

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:31.550
out to red, which are
the most expensive.

00:17:31.550 --> 00:17:34.620
And these five columns
are future annualized

00:17:34.620 --> 00:17:35.700
10-year returns.

00:17:35.700 --> 00:17:37.200
And the only take
away from what you

00:17:37.200 --> 00:17:40.850
should see in this chart is
that most of the green stuff

00:17:40.850 --> 00:17:43.560
is on the right, meaning
your starting points

00:17:43.560 --> 00:17:46.210
when they're cheap--
great future returns.

00:17:46.210 --> 00:17:48.550
And most of the red
stuff is on the left.

00:17:48.550 --> 00:17:50.310
When you pay too
much, in general,

00:17:50.310 --> 00:17:53.090
you get crappy
returns going forward.

00:17:53.090 --> 00:17:55.910
However, it's not
guaranteed, right?

00:17:55.910 --> 00:17:58.670
You see there's three
great returning years

00:17:58.670 --> 00:18:00.710
on the far right
when you started out

00:18:00.710 --> 00:18:02.670
with pretty rich valuations.

00:18:02.670 --> 00:18:05.380
And on the left, there's even
a few green, light greens,

00:18:05.380 --> 00:18:08.640
when markets are cheap that
you had kind of low returns.

00:18:08.640 --> 00:18:11.720
So valuation is not-- it is what
we like to call a blunt tool.

00:18:11.720 --> 00:18:15.620
It is not an exact science,
which makes it challenging

00:18:15.620 --> 00:18:17.200
as well as fun.

00:18:17.200 --> 00:18:19.040
But if you look at
the 10 best times

00:18:19.040 --> 00:18:20.760
to buy stocks in
the past-- I think

00:18:20.760 --> 00:18:25.000
this is 114 years--
awesome returns.

00:18:25.000 --> 00:18:28.230
16% a year, net of inflation.

00:18:28.230 --> 00:18:31.410
You can really compound
massively at that level.

00:18:31.410 --> 00:18:33.780
The starting valuation
was around 11.

00:18:33.780 --> 00:18:35.670
The 10 worst
possible times to be

00:18:35.670 --> 00:18:39.000
buying stocks over
the past 114 years--

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:41.740
negative returns every year.

00:18:41.740 --> 00:18:45.020
Starting valuation was an
average of 23, all right?

00:18:45.020 --> 00:18:48.180
So where do we find
ourselves today?

00:18:48.180 --> 00:18:51.370
A secular bull market starting
point around 11 or a secular

00:18:51.370 --> 00:18:55.280
bear market starting
point around 23.

00:18:55.280 --> 00:18:57.440
The bad news is we're on
the more expensive side.

00:18:57.440 --> 00:18:59.270
There's a caveat, of course.

00:18:59.270 --> 00:19:03.230
This is the PE ratios
versus inflation.

00:19:03.230 --> 00:19:05.590
When inflation is
low and contained--

00:19:05.590 --> 00:19:08.480
let's call this 1% to
4% safe range which

00:19:08.480 --> 00:19:11.580
goes to about here
to here-- people

00:19:11.580 --> 00:19:13.590
are willing to pay
more for stocks, right?

00:19:13.590 --> 00:19:16.200
Because the future is
slightly more certain.

00:19:16.200 --> 00:19:18.799
When inflation is really
high-- think about Argentina,

00:19:18.799 --> 00:19:20.340
think about these
countries that have

00:19:20.340 --> 00:19:22.315
consistent high
inflation-- Venezuela--

00:19:22.315 --> 00:19:23.690
when you're a
business and you're

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:26.420
trying to plan for the
future, it's really difficult.

00:19:26.420 --> 00:19:29.040
On top of that, your future
cash flows are worth less.

00:19:29.040 --> 00:19:31.250
Because every month
you're losing money

00:19:31.250 --> 00:19:33.450
to this erosion of inflation.

00:19:33.450 --> 00:19:34.902
So you'll see a warning sign.

00:19:34.902 --> 00:19:36.860
This may never happen in
the next 10, 20 years.

00:19:36.860 --> 00:19:37.359
Who knows?

00:19:37.359 --> 00:19:37.990
Maybe it will.

00:19:37.990 --> 00:19:40.700
In the '70s, the US had
double digit inflation.

00:19:40.700 --> 00:19:42.570
It's hard for many of
us to comprehend now.

00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:44.630
But thinking about
inflation going up

00:19:44.630 --> 00:19:46.240
that much-- we
live in a world of,

00:19:46.240 --> 00:19:48.730
let's called it 1
and 1/2, 2% inflation

00:19:48.730 --> 00:19:51.240
hopefully right now,
not even that much.

00:19:51.240 --> 00:19:53.000
But the takeaway is,
that until inflation

00:19:53.000 --> 00:19:57.050
gets above really that 3%,
4% kind of upper level,

00:19:57.050 --> 00:19:59.976
people are willing to pay more
for stocks for that certainty.

00:19:59.976 --> 00:20:01.350
Again, they're
not willing to pay

00:20:01.350 --> 00:20:03.510
26, which is off this chart.

00:20:03.510 --> 00:20:05.910
But they're willing to
pay a little bit more.

00:20:05.910 --> 00:20:09.640
There's a lot of criticisms
of this valuation methodology.

00:20:09.640 --> 00:20:14.380
What I want to impress on you,
when you're valuing something,

00:20:14.380 --> 00:20:16.962
most of the valuation
indicators should agree.

00:20:16.962 --> 00:20:19.170
So it doesn't even really
matter if you're using CAPE

00:20:19.170 --> 00:20:20.990
or you're using price
to book or you're

00:20:20.990 --> 00:20:25.870
using cash flows or Buffett's
favorite market cap, the GDP,

00:20:25.870 --> 00:20:27.620
in general they should
say the same thing.

00:20:27.620 --> 00:20:30.070
But, so a lot of people say the
measurement period is too long.

00:20:30.070 --> 00:20:31.610
In our book "Global
Value," we show

00:20:31.610 --> 00:20:34.760
that the best period is
around five to seven years.

00:20:34.760 --> 00:20:36.142
So Ben Graham was right.

00:20:36.142 --> 00:20:37.600
Seven years, I
think, was the best.

00:20:37.600 --> 00:20:38.840
10 is just fine.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:39.660
What's the worst?

00:20:39.660 --> 00:20:41.290
One year earnings.

00:20:41.290 --> 00:20:43.370
What do most analysts
on Wall Street use?

00:20:43.370 --> 00:20:44.820
One year earnings.

00:20:44.820 --> 00:20:48.000
So we don't know why.

00:20:48.000 --> 00:20:50.860
A lot of people say that
ignores depressions or bubbles.

00:20:50.860 --> 00:20:51.854
We're not going to get
into that because we

00:20:51.854 --> 00:20:52.770
don't have enough time today.

00:20:52.770 --> 00:20:55.020
And we certainly aren't going
to get into the accounting,

00:20:55.020 --> 00:20:56.860
talking about reported
and operating earnings.

00:20:56.860 --> 00:20:58.943
But if you want to email
me or you have questions,

00:20:58.943 --> 00:21:00.610
I'm more than happy
to talk about it.

00:21:00.610 --> 00:21:02.845
This is a good chart from
my good friend John Housman

00:21:02.845 --> 00:21:04.220
that goes to show
it doesn't even

00:21:04.220 --> 00:21:06.390
matter what valuation
metric you use.

00:21:06.390 --> 00:21:08.630
These are a bunch of
different models using

00:21:08.630 --> 00:21:11.140
earnings, dividends,
Schiller CAPE.

00:21:11.140 --> 00:21:14.092
This is Buffett's favorite--
10 year market cap GDP.

00:21:14.092 --> 00:21:15.550
And then, how does
it actually work

00:21:15.550 --> 00:21:16.989
in the future 10-year returns?

00:21:16.989 --> 00:21:18.405
And what you can
see in general is

00:21:18.405 --> 00:21:20.790
they all tend to
move together, right?

00:21:20.790 --> 00:21:21.937
Generally.

00:21:21.937 --> 00:21:23.770
They're not going to
be incredibly specific.

00:21:23.770 --> 00:21:27.180
But what this shows is that this
is projected future returns,

00:21:27.180 --> 00:21:27.680
right?

00:21:27.680 --> 00:21:29.912
So it's like the valuation
chart flipped upside down.

00:21:29.912 --> 00:21:31.370
But what it goes
to show-- and it's

00:21:31.370 --> 00:21:33.700
pretty good at
this-- it says, look.

00:21:33.700 --> 00:21:35.670
When were returns
projected to be the worst?

00:21:35.670 --> 00:21:37.020
Late '90s, right?

00:21:37.020 --> 00:21:38.950
That's a terrible time
to be buying stocks.

00:21:38.950 --> 00:21:42.260
But as the market has gone
down, stocks have gotten better.

00:21:42.260 --> 00:21:44.685
And in 2008, stocks
were supposed

00:21:44.685 --> 00:21:45.830
to return double digits.

00:21:45.830 --> 00:21:48.509
But no one wanted to be buying,
even though they were cheap.

00:21:48.509 --> 00:21:50.300
But certainly not a
good buying opportunity

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:52.674
is the early '80s, which is
the start of the biggest bull

00:21:52.674 --> 00:21:55.930
market we've ever seen in
the US, but getting better.

00:21:55.930 --> 00:21:57.965
So again, people like
to think in terms of,

00:21:57.965 --> 00:21:58.840
stocks are expensive.

00:21:58.840 --> 00:21:59.826
They're going to crash.

00:21:59.826 --> 00:22:00.325
Sell.

00:22:00.325 --> 00:22:02.574
When stocks are cheap,
we've got to buy them.

00:22:02.574 --> 00:22:04.240
They're going to go
up to double digits.

00:22:04.240 --> 00:22:06.530
But in reality, it's usually
somewhere in the middle.

00:22:06.530 --> 00:22:09.510
People don't like
hearing something like,

00:22:09.510 --> 00:22:12.400
the future expected returns
are going to be about 4%,

00:22:12.400 --> 00:22:15.610
which is what we think, which
is what the model shows,

00:22:15.610 --> 00:22:18.360
which isn't that exciting.

00:22:18.360 --> 00:22:22.820
So as you think about this,
and thinking about bubbles

00:22:22.820 --> 00:22:24.470
and thinking about
the efficient market

00:22:24.470 --> 00:22:27.450
and not overpaying
for something,

00:22:27.450 --> 00:22:29.750
we think it's important
to understand risk, right?

00:22:29.750 --> 00:22:31.860
And the risk of loss
and the very real risk

00:22:31.860 --> 00:22:33.415
of losing a lot of money.

00:22:33.415 --> 00:22:35.970
A Great Arthur Ashe quote--
either you understand the risk

00:22:35.970 --> 00:22:37.790
or you don't play the game.

00:22:37.790 --> 00:22:39.524
And we have a picture
of the mouse who's

00:22:39.524 --> 00:22:41.190
trying to get the
cheese but being smart

00:22:41.190 --> 00:22:42.390
about it-- wear a helmet.

00:22:47.350 --> 00:22:49.530
And someone on Twitter the
other day said, you know,

00:22:49.530 --> 00:22:52.055
Meb, your CAPE measure,
the Schiller CAPE measure

00:22:52.055 --> 00:22:56.480
is kind of like the difference
of chance of fatality

00:22:56.480 --> 00:22:58.320
if you're driving a car
at 200 miles an hour

00:22:58.320 --> 00:22:59.940
versus five miles
an hour, right?

00:22:59.940 --> 00:23:03.310
You're much more likely to
get into a big wreck fatality

00:23:03.310 --> 00:23:05.800
at 200 miles an hour
then you are at five.

00:23:05.800 --> 00:23:07.330
So that leaves us
with the problem.

00:23:07.330 --> 00:23:09.080
Every pension fund
in the country

00:23:09.080 --> 00:23:11.430
expect 8% returns per year.

00:23:11.430 --> 00:23:14.780
We wrote a paper called,
"What if 8% is 0%?"

00:23:14.780 --> 00:23:18.000
Pension funds investing with
eyes closed, fingers crossed.

00:23:18.000 --> 00:23:19.400
What do you do?

00:23:19.400 --> 00:23:21.500
US bonds yield 2 and 1/2%.

00:23:21.500 --> 00:23:23.947
Stocks should return around 5%.

00:23:23.947 --> 00:23:25.280
That's not that exciting, right?

00:23:25.280 --> 00:23:28.445
Your 4% yield or
4% roughly return.

00:23:28.445 --> 00:23:29.690
The math doesn't work out.

00:23:29.690 --> 00:23:30.940
It doesn't work out for
a lot of institutions

00:23:30.940 --> 00:23:33.460
that are going have really big
troubles with their pension

00:23:33.460 --> 00:23:36.060
funds that will likely
eventually go broke

00:23:36.060 --> 00:23:37.575
in the next 10 to 20, 30 years.

00:23:37.575 --> 00:23:38.325
So what do you do?

00:23:38.325 --> 00:23:41.080
If you're looking at
return, what do you do?

00:23:41.080 --> 00:23:42.157
This is a chart.

00:23:42.157 --> 00:23:43.490
We've never seen anyone do this.

00:23:43.490 --> 00:23:45.110
So we had to go create this.

00:23:45.110 --> 00:23:46.450
We said, all right.

00:23:46.450 --> 00:23:48.880
We live in a global world.

00:23:48.880 --> 00:23:53.040
Let's look at 45 developed and
emerging economies, countries,

00:23:53.040 --> 00:23:56.530
and come up a CAPE ratio
for all of these, right?

00:23:56.530 --> 00:23:59.075
And so we took this
back to the early '80s.

00:23:59.075 --> 00:24:01.700
And in general, the
takeaway of this chart

00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:03.597
is that most things
move together, right?

00:24:03.597 --> 00:24:05.430
And generally, stocks
are correlated, right?

00:24:05.430 --> 00:24:06.962
It's a globalized world, right?

00:24:06.962 --> 00:24:08.670
What happens in the
US is going to affect

00:24:08.670 --> 00:24:12.204
what happens in China and
India and Japan and vice versa.

00:24:12.204 --> 00:24:13.620
So in general,
they move together.

00:24:13.620 --> 00:24:16.390
However, you can see some
pretty wide dispersion

00:24:16.390 --> 00:24:19.200
at certain times
and over the years.

00:24:19.200 --> 00:24:20.820
And then you also
see a few things.

00:24:20.820 --> 00:24:23.634
This massive, massive outlier
over here, this bubble.

00:24:23.634 --> 00:24:25.425
There's a lot of young
faces in the crowds,

00:24:25.425 --> 00:24:27.020
so you probably
don't remember this.

00:24:27.020 --> 00:24:30.300
But Japan in the
late '80s was widely

00:24:30.300 --> 00:24:32.500
expected to take over
the world, right?

00:24:32.500 --> 00:24:34.550
Their companies were better.

00:24:34.550 --> 00:24:35.551
Their cars were better.

00:24:35.551 --> 00:24:37.050
There were more
efficient companies.

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:40.690
The valuation of
their stock market

00:24:40.690 --> 00:24:42.420
is the biggest bubble
we've ever seen.

00:24:42.420 --> 00:24:43.800
And it's not even close.

00:24:43.800 --> 00:24:48.285
They hit a valuation ratio CAPE
of like 95 or maybe it's 99.

00:24:48.285 --> 00:24:48.980
I can't see.

00:24:48.980 --> 00:24:50.510
95, it looks like.

00:24:50.510 --> 00:24:51.260
And so it's funny.

00:24:51.260 --> 00:24:53.301
Because you hear commentators
talk about the lost

00:24:53.301 --> 00:24:55.470
decades in Japan and how
terrible the stock market

00:24:55.470 --> 00:24:58.567
returns have been in the
'90s and 2000s, right?

00:24:58.567 --> 00:25:00.400
No, it's because they
had one of the biggest

00:25:00.400 --> 00:25:01.510
bubbles you've ever seen.

00:25:01.510 --> 00:25:04.570
And it's taken them that
long to work that off, right?

00:25:04.570 --> 00:25:07.590
When did Japan finally get
back to a reasonable valuation?

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:08.730
Only in the last few years.

00:25:08.730 --> 00:25:09.230
What happened?

00:25:09.230 --> 00:25:10.820
Japan is the best
performing stock market

00:25:10.820 --> 00:25:11.778
in the world last year.

00:25:14.160 --> 00:25:15.990
But the efficient
market person will

00:25:15.990 --> 00:25:21.110
say that it was just a good a
time to buy Japan in late 1989

00:25:21.110 --> 00:25:23.281
when the real estate
under the Imperial palace

00:25:23.281 --> 00:25:24.780
was worth more than
the entire state

00:25:24.780 --> 00:25:27.024
of the real estate
of California.

00:25:27.024 --> 00:25:28.440
Things that just
don't make sense.

00:25:28.440 --> 00:25:31.920
But to us, coming up with
this objective measure

00:25:31.920 --> 00:25:34.940
of a fundamental metric,
fundamental anchor,

00:25:34.940 --> 00:25:35.690
can that help you?

00:25:35.690 --> 00:25:37.460
So we said, we
reran the same test.

00:25:37.460 --> 00:25:39.870
Does starting valuation
impact future returns?

00:25:39.870 --> 00:25:42.530
And the answer is, it
does in the same exact way

00:25:42.530 --> 00:25:43.939
that the US did, right?

00:25:43.939 --> 00:25:45.980
The less you pay for
something, the better it is.

00:25:45.980 --> 00:25:49.260
I don't care if it's baseball
cards, a Tesla, whatever

00:25:49.260 --> 00:25:49.930
you think.

00:25:49.930 --> 00:25:52.212
The less you pay for it,
the better it's going to be.

00:25:52.212 --> 00:25:54.170
The more you pay for it,
the worse your returns

00:25:54.170 --> 00:25:55.460
are going to be.

00:25:55.460 --> 00:25:56.560
Where are we right now?

00:25:56.560 --> 00:26:00.200
With foreign developed
markets and foreign emerging,

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:01.930
they're both right around 15.

00:26:01.930 --> 00:26:03.689
So the two red
bars here emerging

00:26:03.689 --> 00:26:04.730
was a little bit cheaper.

00:26:04.730 --> 00:26:09.002
So this bar developed is
a little higher than 15.

00:26:09.002 --> 00:26:11.210
But much better returns than
in the far right bucket,

00:26:11.210 --> 00:26:12.470
which is the US.

00:26:12.470 --> 00:26:13.740
So, much more opportunity.

00:26:13.740 --> 00:26:15.990
What happens if you went
back and said, you know what?

00:26:15.990 --> 00:26:17.740
We're going to only investing
in the cheapest countries.

00:26:17.740 --> 00:26:19.990
Instead of this global
portfolio, what if we just

00:26:19.990 --> 00:26:23.540
invested in the cheapest
25% of countries each year?

00:26:23.540 --> 00:26:25.260
Takes five minutes
a year, rebalance.

00:26:25.260 --> 00:26:27.450
Well, that would
have done fantastic.

00:26:27.450 --> 00:26:29.170
So this is what the
global portfolio

00:26:29.170 --> 00:26:29.820
would have looked like.

00:26:29.820 --> 00:26:31.736
The top CAPE, which is
the cheapest countries,

00:26:31.736 --> 00:26:33.730
did a much better job
than the bottom CAPE,

00:26:33.730 --> 00:26:35.710
the expensive countries, OK?

00:26:35.710 --> 00:26:36.980
Again, not complicated.

00:26:36.980 --> 00:26:38.640
But buying value works.

00:26:38.640 --> 00:26:39.704
It has worked over time.

00:26:39.704 --> 00:26:41.120
Enormous amount
of literature that

00:26:41.120 --> 00:26:43.790
shows this investing
in stocks worked great.

00:26:43.790 --> 00:26:45.790
This is what the equity
curve looks like, right?

00:26:45.790 --> 00:26:49.720
This is a logarithmic chart
to equalize returns over time.

00:26:49.720 --> 00:26:53.700
But again, yellow line, that's
investing in what's expensive.

00:26:53.700 --> 00:26:54.770
Not a bright idea.

00:26:54.770 --> 00:26:57.815
Black line, buy and hold
of all the countries.

00:26:57.815 --> 00:26:59.940
The blue and red lines are
two different variations

00:26:59.940 --> 00:27:00.898
of buying the cheapest.

00:27:00.898 --> 00:27:03.290
One is you said, you know what?

00:27:03.290 --> 00:27:06.682
It probably makes sense
to invest in the cheapest.

00:27:06.682 --> 00:27:09.140
But only invest in the cheapest
when they are the cheapest.

00:27:09.140 --> 00:27:10.510
What if everything is expensive?

00:27:10.510 --> 00:27:12.290
So like, in the late
'90s, for example, right?

00:27:12.290 --> 00:27:13.750
You don't want to be
investing in stocks

00:27:13.750 --> 00:27:14.958
when everything is expensive.

00:27:14.958 --> 00:27:18.790
So we use the absolute
metric caps of around,

00:27:18.790 --> 00:27:21.880
I think it was 18 in the book--
maybe it was 20-- to say,

00:27:21.880 --> 00:27:22.630
you know what?

00:27:22.630 --> 00:27:25.310
If things get that much, we'll
start to move the cash, right?

00:27:25.310 --> 00:27:28.080
And so you'll come with a little
bit less volatile portfolio.

00:27:28.080 --> 00:27:30.470
Same returns over
time, but avoid

00:27:30.470 --> 00:27:34.500
some of the big draw downs
and losses of buy and hold.

00:27:34.500 --> 00:27:36.200
But what's really
interesting-- and this

00:27:36.200 --> 00:27:40.860
happens a lot in various
fields-- is I have a buddy,

00:27:40.860 --> 00:27:43.350
John Bollinger
says, you know, all

00:27:43.350 --> 00:27:45.347
the information is
in the tails, right?

00:27:45.347 --> 00:27:46.680
So the ends of the distribution.

00:27:46.680 --> 00:27:48.864
That's when things get
really interesting.

00:27:48.864 --> 00:27:51.030
And so, what we call is--
there's a famous investing

00:27:51.030 --> 00:27:53.705
phrase that says, investing when
there's blood on the streets.

00:27:53.705 --> 00:27:55.080
Hopefully not
literally, but when

00:27:55.080 --> 00:27:56.980
things are really, really bad.

00:27:56.980 --> 00:27:59.860
So we call this at a
CAPE ratio below seven,

00:27:59.860 --> 00:28:01.450
which doesn't happen that much.

00:28:01.450 --> 00:28:03.910
It's only happened in
the US a couple times.

00:28:03.910 --> 00:28:05.347
Future returns are fantastic.

00:28:05.347 --> 00:28:07.555
One, three, five years,
you're compounding your money

00:28:07.555 --> 00:28:09.917
at 20% percent a year.

00:28:09.917 --> 00:28:10.750
What's the opposite?

00:28:10.750 --> 00:28:11.710
Bubble, right?

00:28:11.710 --> 00:28:14.670
Where the markets are
really expensive-- over 45.

00:28:14.670 --> 00:28:16.170
So that's the peak
of the US, right?

00:28:16.170 --> 00:28:21.500
But anyone remembers
back to 2006, 2007,

00:28:21.500 --> 00:28:24.160
if you were investing
then, the BRICs, right?

00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:26.817
This expression-- Brazil,
Russia, India, and China.

00:28:26.817 --> 00:28:28.150
That's where you want to invest.

00:28:28.150 --> 00:28:29.620
That's where the world's going.

00:28:29.620 --> 00:28:33.160
What they didn't mention
was that China and India

00:28:33.160 --> 00:28:34.920
were both trading
at CAPEs above 40.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:37.121
I think China hit 65, right?

00:28:37.121 --> 00:28:38.870
And so China has had
horrific stock market

00:28:38.870 --> 00:28:40.190
returns since then.

00:28:40.190 --> 00:28:42.190
Is anyone talking about
China that much anymore?

00:28:42.190 --> 00:28:43.000
No.

00:28:43.000 --> 00:28:47.460
But China is at a
great valuation now.

00:28:47.460 --> 00:28:49.340
But this is what
happens over and over.

00:28:49.340 --> 00:28:52.120
People are much more interested
in investing here-- they're

00:28:52.120 --> 00:28:55.080
excited because returns have
been great-- then there.

00:28:55.080 --> 00:28:58.580
It's really hard to
invest in the low markets.

00:28:58.580 --> 00:29:01.910
Part of that is simply
behavioral, right?

00:29:01.910 --> 00:29:03.840
All the news is bad, right?

00:29:03.840 --> 00:29:05.470
The news is usually terrible.

00:29:05.470 --> 00:29:07.110
So let's give you
some common examples.

00:29:07.110 --> 00:29:07.818
Where are we now?

00:29:07.818 --> 00:29:11.630
I just updated this at
the end of last month.

00:29:11.630 --> 00:29:13.860
You look at the left.

00:29:13.860 --> 00:29:16.360
The cheapest markets
in the world-- Greece

00:29:16.360 --> 00:29:19.910
had the lowest valuation we've
ever seen at a value of 2

00:29:19.910 --> 00:29:22.060
in the summer of 2012.

00:29:22.060 --> 00:29:23.740
Greece is now up 200%.

00:29:23.740 --> 00:29:25.710
Their stock market
off the bottom.

00:29:25.710 --> 00:29:29.140
Russia hit a value around
five, maybe got down to four

00:29:29.140 --> 00:29:30.700
a couple months ago.

00:29:30.700 --> 00:29:34.310
Ireland, Hungary, Austria,
Italy, most of Europe, right?

00:29:34.310 --> 00:29:36.280
But where the
returns are best is

00:29:36.280 --> 00:29:40.490
when things go from truly
horrific to merely less bad.

00:29:40.490 --> 00:29:42.471
Russia is a perfect example.

00:29:42.471 --> 00:29:43.970
We've been on TV
the last few months

00:29:43.970 --> 00:29:46.090
pounding the table
for Russia, saying

00:29:46.090 --> 00:29:48.790
Russia is cheap on every
valuation metric we can find,

00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:51.390
to which all the TV anchors
say, well, what about Crimea?

00:29:51.390 --> 00:29:52.420
What about Putin?

00:29:52.420 --> 00:29:54.570
What about all these
things that are happening?

00:29:54.570 --> 00:29:57.790
But that's when you
want to be investing.

00:29:57.790 --> 00:29:59.287
Sir [INAUDIBLE] famous quote.

00:29:59.287 --> 00:30:01.120
He says, don't ask me
where things are best.

00:30:01.120 --> 00:30:02.440
That's the wrong question.

00:30:02.440 --> 00:30:04.230
Ask me where things
are the worst.

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:06.660
The challenge with why this
strategy works and will

00:30:06.660 --> 00:30:09.550
continue to work--
imagine going home

00:30:09.550 --> 00:30:13.182
to your wife, your husband,
sister, brother, neighbor,

00:30:13.182 --> 00:30:14.140
and say, you know what?

00:30:14.140 --> 00:30:16.390
I heard this great
presentation today.

00:30:16.390 --> 00:30:20.930
I'm putting my money into
Greece and in Russia.

00:30:20.930 --> 00:30:24.760
Now, the next four-- the next--
you'll get slapped or divorced

00:30:24.760 --> 00:30:25.650
or what not.

00:30:25.650 --> 00:30:27.480
In my industry, you'll
get fired, right,

00:30:27.480 --> 00:30:28.820
as a money manager.

00:30:31.730 --> 00:30:39.570
And it's funny because
the European names--

00:30:39.570 --> 00:30:44.540
the European names don't elicit
as much hatred right now,

00:30:44.540 --> 00:30:45.140
right?

00:30:45.140 --> 00:30:47.350
Most people say Hungary,
Austria, Italy, OK.

00:30:47.350 --> 00:30:48.160
Interesting.

00:30:48.160 --> 00:30:51.940
You go back a couple years when
the euro was disintegrating--

00:30:51.940 --> 00:30:54.380
no one wanted to be
investing in those countries.

00:30:54.380 --> 00:30:57.350
Italy-- second best stock
market in the world this year.

00:30:57.350 --> 00:30:59.500
It's up, I think, almost 20%.

00:30:59.500 --> 00:31:01.950
So when things-- as
the news flow recedes,

00:31:01.950 --> 00:31:04.620
Russia from the bottom--
here's the dumb things you

00:31:04.620 --> 00:31:05.910
here at the bottom, right?

00:31:05.910 --> 00:31:09.940
US government press secretary
goes to Twitter and says,

00:31:09.940 --> 00:31:11.400
someone asked him about Russia.

00:31:11.400 --> 00:31:12.860
And he says, you know what?

00:31:12.860 --> 00:31:14.960
I would be selling Russian
stocks if I were you.

00:31:14.960 --> 00:31:17.880
In fact, I would
be shorting them.

00:31:17.880 --> 00:31:20.740
This is the press secretary
giving this advice

00:31:20.740 --> 00:31:23.960
to the general public of not
only selling Russian stocks,

00:31:23.960 --> 00:31:26.150
but shorting them, OK?

00:31:26.150 --> 00:31:28.450
He's suggesting, first of
all, telling the investment

00:31:28.450 --> 00:31:30.220
public, short anything--
horrific advice.

00:31:30.220 --> 00:31:32.245
You can lose your
entire account.

00:31:32.245 --> 00:31:34.870
Talking about shorting a market
that goes up and down 5% a day,

00:31:34.870 --> 00:31:36.515
the volatility is
off the charts.

00:31:36.515 --> 00:31:38.640
And oh, by the way, it's
the second cheapest market

00:31:38.640 --> 00:31:39.320
in the world.

00:31:39.320 --> 00:31:41.280
What's happened since then?

00:31:41.280 --> 00:31:43.730
I like to-- not patting
myself on the back,

00:31:43.730 --> 00:31:46.410
Russia is up, what
25% from the bottom.

00:31:46.410 --> 00:31:48.190
Press secretary no
longer has a job.

00:31:48.190 --> 00:31:51.134
I'm not saying
that's why-- related.

00:31:51.134 --> 00:31:52.550
But if you look
at the right side,

00:31:52.550 --> 00:31:54.360
these are the most expensive.

00:31:54.360 --> 00:31:56.340
I was really unpopular
in the last year.

00:31:56.340 --> 00:32:00.210
