So avoidance, I
think, is just fine.

00:51:37.190 --> 00:51:40.080
Shorting, unlike
the press secretary,

00:51:40.080 --> 00:51:42.640
I wouldn't recommend it.

00:51:42.640 --> 00:51:47.020
OK the question is, US has
exposure to a globalize world,

00:51:47.020 --> 00:51:47.740
right?

00:51:47.740 --> 00:51:53.080
Roughly what, half of the US
revenues come from abroad?

00:51:53.080 --> 00:51:56.480
But vice versa-- as the
world gets more globalized,

00:51:56.480 --> 00:52:00.540
much of the countries abroad--
China, Mexico, Canada-- all

00:52:00.540 --> 00:52:02.420
have exposure to
the US too, right?

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:05.690
So our opinion is that we
just assume correlations

00:52:05.690 --> 00:52:08.920
of one-- very high correlation
of stock markets, right?

00:52:08.920 --> 00:52:12.030
So in that world, it comes
to a more simple question.

00:52:12.030 --> 00:52:14.330
It's not where
revenues come from,

00:52:14.330 --> 00:52:16.420
but where is it just cheapest?

00:52:16.420 --> 00:52:18.400
So you're getting
foreign exposure--

00:52:18.400 --> 00:52:21.230
so you can get foreign
exposure in the US at half.

00:52:21.230 --> 00:52:24.440
Or you can get foreign exposure
elsewhere for much cheaper.

00:52:24.440 --> 00:52:26.940
So it's more important to
us in a globalized world

00:52:26.940 --> 00:52:28.300
just to buy what's cheapest.

00:52:28.300 --> 00:52:30.310
If the opportunity
set is similar

00:52:30.310 --> 00:52:32.860
and they're highly correlated,
which they are-- I mean,

00:52:32.860 --> 00:52:33.401
it's not one.

00:52:33.401 --> 00:52:36.700
But global stocks in general
are up around 70%, 80%.

00:52:36.700 --> 00:52:37.280
That's great.

00:52:37.280 --> 00:52:40.610
Because then the
valuation means even more.

00:52:40.610 --> 00:52:43.880
AUDIENCE: When you're looking
at returns of global stocks,

00:52:43.880 --> 00:52:46.510
are you taking into account
currency fluctuations?

00:52:46.510 --> 00:52:49.010
MEBANE FABER: Oh, I knew that
question-- the question always

00:52:49.010 --> 00:52:49.509
comes up.

00:52:49.509 --> 00:52:50.270
Good question.

00:52:50.270 --> 00:52:52.550
Question is, what
about currencies?

00:52:52.550 --> 00:52:55.010
And this is quite
a simple sounding

00:52:55.010 --> 00:52:58.180
question but a
much longer answer.

00:52:58.180 --> 00:53:00.600
When you're think
about currencies,

00:53:00.600 --> 00:53:06.972
there's a quote that says,
currencies aren't-- currencies

00:53:06.972 --> 00:53:07.680
aren't difficult.

00:53:07.680 --> 00:53:09.160
They're just confusing.

00:53:09.160 --> 00:53:11.060
And Americans are the
worst at it, right?

00:53:11.060 --> 00:53:12.851
Most people, when they
think of currencies,

00:53:12.851 --> 00:53:14.880
they think of, all right.

00:53:14.880 --> 00:53:15.870
The peso is going down.

00:53:15.870 --> 00:53:18.820
It's now cheaper to go
buy steaks in Argentina.

00:53:18.820 --> 00:53:21.137
Or maybe it's getting expensive
to go skiing in Europe.

00:53:21.137 --> 00:53:21.720
And that's it.

00:53:21.720 --> 00:53:24.270
They don't think about
them in terms of investing.

00:53:24.270 --> 00:53:25.830
They do have a very real impact.

00:53:25.830 --> 00:53:28.740
Over time, currency
real returns--

00:53:28.740 --> 00:53:31.800
because currencies adjust
for inflation-- over time,

00:53:31.800 --> 00:53:34.060
currency real
returns are stable,

00:53:34.060 --> 00:53:35.167
keyword being over time.

00:53:35.167 --> 00:53:37.000
In any given year, you
could have a currency

00:53:37.000 --> 00:53:41.260
like Japan last year move
20%, 30%, which is a lot.

00:53:41.260 --> 00:53:44.490
So I'm actually, if you
have no value added way

00:53:44.490 --> 00:53:47.954
to predict currencies, which
I would argue most don't, I

00:53:47.954 --> 00:53:50.370
would argue you have to choose
one side or the other year.

00:53:50.370 --> 00:53:51.800
You're either agnostic and
you say, you know what?

00:53:51.800 --> 00:53:53.424
I'm going to do it
from US dollar base.

00:53:53.424 --> 00:53:56.330
Or you hedge all your
currency exposure.

00:53:56.330 --> 00:53:58.060
But you pick one
and stick with it.

00:53:58.060 --> 00:54:02.200
And over time, they'll
have the same performance.

00:54:02.200 --> 00:54:04.590
And then a follow up
is, can you do things

00:54:04.590 --> 00:54:06.610
in currencies the
same way you do

00:54:06.610 --> 00:54:08.810
in stocks and bonds that
have outsized returns?

00:54:08.810 --> 00:54:12.900
So yes, you can actually index
currencies with basic value

00:54:12.900 --> 00:54:16.180
trend, momentum
carry strategies that

00:54:16.180 --> 00:54:18.410
perform great and don't
correlate to stocks.

00:54:18.410 --> 00:54:21.610
But that's the point of a
whole other two hour talk.

00:54:21.610 --> 00:54:23.350
So you guys have
me back in 2015.

00:54:23.350 --> 00:54:25.010
We'll talk about currency.

00:54:25.010 --> 00:54:25.970
So I'm agnostic.

00:54:25.970 --> 00:54:28.640
But it makes a big
difference in the short term.

00:54:28.640 --> 00:54:31.125
AUDIENCE: In terms of
the current valuation,

00:54:31.125 --> 00:54:34.790
it seems to me that Warren
Buffett, Joe Greenblad and also

00:54:34.790 --> 00:54:37.030
Howard [INAUDIBLE] post--
I think all of them

00:54:37.030 --> 00:54:38.940
said it's [INAUDIBLE] right now?

00:54:38.940 --> 00:54:41.890
And only one of
note that is kind

00:54:41.890 --> 00:54:48.440
of bearish in the long
term is [INAUDIBLE].

00:54:48.440 --> 00:54:51.540
So can you reconcile with them?

00:54:51.540 --> 00:54:53.510
Because if Warren
Buffett and Joe

00:54:53.510 --> 00:54:57.710
Greenblad those said that it's
[INAUDIBLE] it's hard for me

00:54:57.710 --> 00:55:00.460
to think that it's expensive.

00:55:00.460 --> 00:55:02.840
MEBANE FABER: Well,
if you use Buffett's

00:55:02.840 --> 00:55:06.640
own favorite valuation metric,
which is market cap to GNP,

00:55:06.640 --> 00:55:08.970
stocks are very expensive.

00:55:08.970 --> 00:55:11.690
You also always have
to ask why people

00:55:11.690 --> 00:55:13.020
have the opinion they do.

00:55:13.020 --> 00:55:16.590
If you're a money manager and
have all your money invested

00:55:16.590 --> 00:55:20.600
long stocks in the US, are you
going to say they're expensive?

00:55:20.600 --> 00:55:22.780
Probably not.

00:55:22.780 --> 00:55:24.500
So it's challenging.

00:55:24.500 --> 00:55:27.196
And going back to the
intro of the speech,

00:55:27.196 --> 00:55:29.070
I think you should ignore
all of them, right?

00:55:29.070 --> 00:55:30.570
Everyone's going
to have an opinion.

00:55:30.570 --> 00:55:31.896
Just like, you know.

00:55:31.896 --> 00:55:33.494
A guy or girl walks by.

00:55:33.494 --> 00:55:35.410
10 people are going to
have different opinions

00:55:35.410 --> 00:55:38.020
and say, well, I like
him, I don't like him.

00:55:38.020 --> 00:55:39.190
He's attractive, he's not.

00:55:39.190 --> 00:55:39.982
Whatever it may be.

00:55:39.982 --> 00:55:41.564
But that's what makes
a market, right?

00:55:41.564 --> 00:55:43.330
There's someone who's
bullish on US stocks

00:55:43.330 --> 00:55:46.410
in 1999 the same as
someone who is bearish.

00:55:46.410 --> 00:55:48.612
So that's why it's
important to me

00:55:48.612 --> 00:55:49.820
to have an objective measure.

00:55:49.820 --> 00:55:50.820
I don't care what it is.

00:55:50.820 --> 00:55:53.910
You can use price, sales price,
book price, cash flow, GDP,

00:55:53.910 --> 00:55:54.860
enterprise, EBITDA.

00:55:54.860 --> 00:55:57.500
By the way, all of those
say US stocks are expensive.

00:55:57.500 --> 00:55:59.492
There's not one that doesn't.

00:55:59.492 --> 00:56:01.200
But you have to have
an objective metric.

00:56:01.200 --> 00:56:05.620
Otherwise, you're just-- what
we have found in the literature,

00:56:05.620 --> 00:56:07.650
and this applies to
almost every field,

00:56:07.650 --> 00:56:11.565
is experts are horrific at
forecasting, including our US

00:56:11.565 --> 00:56:13.190
government, the
Federal Reserve, right?

00:56:13.190 --> 00:56:15.520
They are horrific at
forecasting the future.

00:56:15.520 --> 00:56:17.500
But if you have an
objective metric and say,

00:56:17.500 --> 00:56:21.140
all right, stocks very well
could go up 50% from here.

00:56:21.140 --> 00:56:23.450
But all that's doing is
mortgaging the future.

00:56:23.450 --> 00:56:25.025
So it's unexciting
to say, I think

00:56:25.025 --> 00:56:26.400
stocks are going
to do 4% a year.

00:56:26.400 --> 00:56:27.233
That's not terrible.

00:56:27.233 --> 00:56:29.340
It's better than
2 and 1/2% bond.

00:56:29.340 --> 00:56:31.350
But is it worth taking the risk?

00:56:31.350 --> 00:56:33.740
I would much rather invest
in the really cheap stuff,

00:56:33.740 --> 00:56:36.470
most of which happens to
be in Europe right now.

00:56:36.470 --> 00:56:38.890
So as I said on Twitter,
cheer for the US on Sunday,

00:56:38.890 --> 00:56:40.375
but buy Portuguese stocks.

00:56:44.090 --> 00:56:46.580
AUDIENCE: So how do you
avoid the value trap?

00:56:46.580 --> 00:56:48.650
For example, if Greece
had defaulted an exited

00:56:48.650 --> 00:56:52.124
from the euro, even buying at
two might have been expensive.

00:56:52.124 --> 00:56:54.040
MEBANE FABER: How do you
avoid the value trap?

00:56:54.040 --> 00:56:58.170
Well, question is,
how do you avoid

00:56:58.170 --> 00:56:59.670
buying a falling
knife and something

00:56:59.670 --> 00:57:01.000
it's cheap getting cheaper?

00:57:01.000 --> 00:57:02.810
And there's a couple
ways to lessen

00:57:02.810 --> 00:57:04.580
the impact of it,
the first being,

00:57:04.580 --> 00:57:08.470
diversify and buy a basket
of 10 countries, right?

00:57:08.470 --> 00:57:11.210
So, we own Czechoslovakia,
lot of those countries

00:57:11.210 --> 00:57:12.590
we talked about--
Brazil, Russia.

00:57:12.590 --> 00:57:14.715
One may be doing poorly,
another one's-- hopefully,

00:57:14.715 --> 00:57:16.798
that's-- same thing as you
buy a basket of stocks.

00:57:16.798 --> 00:57:17.900
Helps diversify the risk.

00:57:17.900 --> 00:57:19.330
Doesn't totally diversify it.

00:57:19.330 --> 00:57:21.621
Because right now, for example,
most of those countries

00:57:21.621 --> 00:57:23.240
are in Europe, in
emerging Europe.

00:57:23.240 --> 00:57:28.470
So you're getting exposure
that very well may do poorly.

00:57:28.470 --> 00:57:32.350
Another way to do it is
having a long enough horizon.

00:57:32.350 --> 00:57:36.660
Give it a number of years
to be able to recover.

00:57:36.660 --> 00:57:40.430
And that's a big key with
buying the really cheap stuff.

00:57:40.430 --> 00:57:42.600
It's hard to watch
something go down.

00:57:42.600 --> 00:57:44.940
The last way is
to-- for those who

00:57:44.940 --> 00:57:47.370
have followed my
research for a long time,

00:57:47.370 --> 00:57:49.850
know that we write a lot
about global maccarone trends.

00:57:49.850 --> 00:57:53.840
And so another way is use
trend following metrics, right,

00:57:53.840 --> 00:57:56.264
which would help you
say, all right, I'm

00:57:56.264 --> 00:57:57.680
going to buy this
something cheap,

00:57:57.680 --> 00:58:00.960
but only once it starts going
back up and has a nice trend.

00:58:00.960 --> 00:58:03.447
And then you still have an
objective buy and sell rule.

00:58:03.447 --> 00:58:05.280
You buy when it's above
the long term trend.

00:58:05.280 --> 00:58:06.620
You sell when it's below.

00:58:06.620 --> 00:58:09.130
Historically, that
doesn't add to returns.

00:58:09.130 --> 00:58:13.290
But it vastly reduces the
drawdown and volatility.

00:58:13.290 --> 00:58:16.160
So my favorite intersection
would be value and momentum.

00:58:16.160 --> 00:58:18.080
So buying what's cheap,
but also going up.

00:58:18.080 --> 00:58:19.680
So there's a number
of ways to try

00:58:19.680 --> 00:58:22.980
to minimize the
damage it can do.

00:58:22.980 --> 00:58:25.630
But it's part of
buying what's cheap

00:58:25.630 --> 00:58:32.210
is you're not ever
missing all the risk.

00:58:32.210 --> 00:58:35.380
AUDIENCE: So say you've decided
to invest in certain countries.

00:58:35.380 --> 00:58:37.972
How do you determine what
to buy in that country?

00:58:37.972 --> 00:58:39.430
MEBANE FABER: So
the simplest would

00:58:39.430 --> 00:58:41.410
be to buy the market
cap weighted index.

00:58:41.410 --> 00:58:43.305
Highly liquid companies.

00:58:43.305 --> 00:58:44.930
We go a step further,
which we actually

00:58:44.930 --> 00:58:46.710
didn't publish in our book.

00:58:46.710 --> 00:58:50.310
And out of the 30 biggest
companies in that country,

00:58:50.310 --> 00:58:51.560
we buy the 10 cheapest.

00:58:51.560 --> 00:58:53.700
Use a bunch of just
different valuation metrics.

00:58:53.700 --> 00:58:55.830
So it's almost like a
dogs of the Dow approach.

00:58:55.830 --> 00:58:57.625
So our [? ETF, ?]
for example, will

00:58:57.625 --> 00:59:00.570
own about 100 stocks
in those countries.

00:59:00.570 --> 00:59:03.540
That adds about
another percent return

00:59:03.540 --> 00:59:05.600
on top of just buying
the market cap.

00:59:05.600 --> 00:59:07.891
Because you're getting away
from market cap in general.

00:59:07.891 --> 00:59:09.680
You're buying the
worst of the worst.

00:59:09.680 --> 00:59:11.220
But as the individual
investor, it's

00:59:11.220 --> 00:59:14.840
really challenging to buy
individual foreign stocks

00:59:14.840 --> 00:59:16.870
in general for a
big enough portfolio

00:59:16.870 --> 00:59:19.420
to diversify 100 stocks
in all these countries

00:59:19.420 --> 00:59:21.082
around the world.

00:59:21.082 --> 00:59:22.970
And it's a huge pain
with taxes, too.

00:59:22.970 --> 00:59:26.570
So one way is to buy
country funds like ETFs.

00:59:26.570 --> 00:59:29.390
Even if you don't buy
ours, you can buy-- just

00:59:29.390 --> 00:59:30.840
moving away from
the US in general

00:59:30.840 --> 00:59:33.296
I think is a great first step.

00:59:33.296 --> 00:59:34.170
Thanks for having me.

00:59:34.170 --> 00:59:36.500
I'll stick around
for a few minutes.

